			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Verifiable Parse Table Composition for Deterministic Parsing</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AugustSchwerdfeger.html">August Schwerdfeger</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_15">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_15</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The paper focuses on composing parse tables/grammars while preserving deterministic parsing—composition is the key operation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> ‘Verifiable’ parsing results imply formal guarantees/proofs about determinism/correctness.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Parse-table composition supports modular parser construction, a core capability in language tooling.
</li></ul></li></ul>
